“Work starts at eight. I think I could do something in the meantime. True, I always walk to the office at this time, but let's break the cycle.”

"I was going to cook, eat, shower, maybe make my bed. Instead, I sat at my messy apartment's table, staring out aimlessly through the window. The chamomile tea went cold in my hand. I stared out for that long. The city was meant to be enormous. So much for a hundred thousand people! But at this hour, even in the city centre, only one person was present. Her."

"The blue light shines perfectly on her. That type of blue light you get before sunrise. That same, sleepy light that would put me into sleep as a kid." 

"She was so young. So full of energy. While I could see we were the same age, I lacked the sunshine she had in her heart. I was a sad man. I had a boring life, nothing to look into nor do the next day." 

"Her happiness was something I'd have on a hot summer night eating slices of watermelon. She was smiling. Grinning ear to ear. Jumping around, as if nobody saw her. While, to her it was a correct assumption, to me it wasn't. She clearly wasn't scared of what others thought."

I" would have preferred if I was more observant, not only staring at her young cheerfulness. I could have ran down, and pushed her away from that red car. It was drifting. Even going on the sidewalk. It looked like some maniac got into that car, or someone that had no business driving a car."

"If I didn't break the cycle I would be in the same position she was. Same position she was. Same position she was. The car would've hit me."

"I was meant to die.I was meant to die.

She should be alive. She should be alive."

"The voice that came out of me was something only I was meant to hear. It was raw, disgusting. Something like a banshee being burned." 

'Hey, why did you scream so loud! You woke me up!' "A noise banged on the other side of the wall. I couldn't care less."
